4. Technical Pipeline
Step 1A — Data Cleaning
Each of the 7 CSV files was cleaned individually:
•	studentAssessment: 173 missing scores filled with 0; 'submitted' flag column added
•	studentRegistration: dropped_out boolean created from date_unregistration; NaN dates filled with -1
•	vle: week_from/week_to NaN values filled with 0

Step 1B — Building the Master Table
All files merged into a single master table of 28,785 students × 32 columns.
•	Calculated days_early = assessment due date - submission date
•	Created submission_status labels: early / on_time / slightly_late / very_late
•	Aggregated per-student signals: avg_score, score_std, late_submissions, early_submissions
•	Calculated score_trend using linear regression slope (numpy.polyfit)
•	Merged VLE engagement signals: total_clicks, unique_resources, engagement_level

Step 2A — Feature Engineering: Normalization
10 raw signals normalized to 0–1 scale using MinMaxScaler so all features have equal weight in the model:
avg_score, score_trend, total_clicks, late_submissions, early_submissions, avg_days_early, num_of_prev_attempts, score_std, num_assessments, unique_resources

Step 2B — Composite Risk Scores
Three composite scores built from normalized signals:

Risk Score	Formula	Interpretation
academic_risk	(1 - avg_score) × 0.5 + (1 - trend) × 0.3 + score_std × 0.2	How far from expected academic performance
engagement_risk	(1 - clicks) × 0.5 + (1 - resources) × 0.3 + (1 - early_subs) × 0.2	How disconnected from the platform
persistence_risk	prev_attempts × 0.4 + late_subs × 0.4 + dropped_out × 0.2	Pattern of repeated difficulty

Step 2C — Root Cause Labeling
Each student assigned one root cause using rule-based logic on their signals. These labels become the training target for the classifier.

Step 3 — Root Cause Classifier
Three models trained and compared:

Model	Accuracy	Notes
Decision Tree	89.7%	Most interpretable, max depth 6
Random Forest	90.4%	100 trees, balanced class weights
XGBoost	92.5%	Winner — sequential boosting, learning rate 0.1

XGBoost selected as the final model. Top 3 most important features:
•	avg_score_norm → 0.452 importance (45.2% of model decision)
•	academic_risk → 0.183 importance (18.3%)
•	score_trend_norm → 0.138 importance (13.8%)
 
